      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>4 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=141146&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101335363782740></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101335363782740><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101335363782740>the gnolls of Lake Rathetear; a clue to power</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101335363782740#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=141146><span id= >Igon</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>4 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Feb 10th 11:10 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>During my time at the Aviak village, I heard many stories of the problems gnolls were causing in Lake Rathetear. It seems they set up a village at the mouth of the canyon that led to the lake, making it nearly impossible for anyone to advance to the water. The gnolls swarmed all adventurers who dared to approach their village and the canyon was quickly becoming a boneyard of dwarves, humans, elves and others.<br>Since I felt I had adequately pacified the bird-people, I decided to head for the lake and see if I could solve this problem. I was accompianied on my journey by the female druid Shandel.<br>We arrived at the mouth of the canyon which led from the Karana Plains to Lake Rathetear. We spent several minutes using our magic to prepare ourselves for what lie ahead, then proceeded to the gnoll village.<br>The village was nothing more than a few ramshackle shelters at the mouth of the canyon. I scouted around and saw that the lake was just beyond the village. The gnolls had constructed a dock at the site and a gnoll magic user with a familiar seemed to be waiting for something there. As I finished my trek around the village, I counted no more than half a dozen gnolls and felt confident Shandel and myself could end this threat ... if we could avoid the attention of the caster while we dispatched the rest. Magic is a variable that is just too unpredictable to take lightly.<br>I returned to Shandel and gave her the details of my recon. She agreed with my assessment of the caster. Our plan was to avoid the caster by attacking gnolls one-by-one, with Shandel ready to call upon the power of nature to entangle any extra gnolls who became aware of our presence.<br>As I snuck towards our first intended victim, I heard a splash from the direction of the lake, then a shout, followed quickly by an explosion. I turned to see a halfling sprinting through the camp, with the caster in pursuit. This of course alerted all the other gnolls, who joined the chase.<br>The halfling seemed to have magical speed as he ran past us and out of the canyon. He escaped safely ... leaving seven gnolls to bear down upon Shandel and I.<br>Shandel managed to entangle two of them before the mob reached us. I dove into the pile to prevent them from reaching her, my focus on the caster. As I attacked what I perceived to be the biggest threat, I was shocked to notice that several more of the creatures also had the ability to wield magic. They used their powers to create illness in my body. I felt feverish and poison creeped through my veins.<br>I was unable to keep them all from Shandel, as the gnolls proved to be far more powerful than we had originally estimated. Two snuck past me and assaulted her. She could not stand against their combined might and began to retreat farther into the canyon. I was holding my ground, but the three who remained seemed destined to overpower me at any minute. The situation would only worsen when the other two gnolls freed themselves from their bonds.<br>Suddenly, a burst of swirling colors filled the air and the gnolls dropped their attack to stare at it, mesmerized. I felt my wounds begin to heal. I turned briefly to see a halfling and human, both wielding magic and both ready to assist me in this battle. I saluted them, let out a mighty bellow, and launched myself at the main caster once again. He regained himself long enough to put up slight resistance, but he hit the ground dead before he could cast any more evil spells.<br>The tide had turned. The halfling and I picked off the gnolls one-by-one, while the human kept the attention of the rest with his swirling display. As the last one fell, I turned to thank my new companions once again.<br>The halfling was named Ooomid and wielded the power of nature as did Shandel. The human, Mecha, identified himself as an enchanter. They told me they had seen Shandel retreating through the canyon and assisted her. She had told them of my plight, but her wounds were too grave for her to assist in the battle. However, they assured me that she was safe and would recover soon.<br>I suggested that after a brief rest, we check out the village one more time to ensure that it was empty. Ooomid and I ventured into the camp ... at the exact same time as a gnoll patrol returned. After a few stunned seconds on the side of both groups, we attacked. The gnolls returned the favor and we gave ground in an attempt to lead them back to Mecha, our magical backup. We manuevered the beasts back to our camp, where Mecha and a healed Shandel joined the fray. What could have been a difficult battle turned into a rout.<br>After another short rest, I journeyed back to the gnoll camp one more time. Finding no more evidence of life, I was satisfied that we had, if not eliminated, at least seriously crippled the gnoll force in the area. I made my report to my comrades. Mecha and Ooomid were on their way to another area of the lake and headed off. Shandel decided to join them. I had business to attend to in Qeynos so I went the opposite direction, but not before assuring them I would be willing to fight by their side any day.<br>******<br>The journey to Qeynos on foot is a long one. Much of the trip is along a river called The Serpent. There is not much danger on the banks of this river, despite its somewhat-ominous name. A few bandit camps are the biggest threat for less-experienced adventurers, but I had nothing to fear from the likes of them.<br>The miles began to drag on as I entered what are considered the Western Plains of Karana. I had decided to continue traveling at night rather than rest, but as midnight approached I felt it was time to make camp. Just as I prepared to stop, I spotted a lone figure standing at the bank of The Serpent, staring off into the water. Thinking him another bandit, I decided to scare him off or destroy him. There would be no safe camp here.<br>As I approached though, I noticed that this man's armor gleamed too brightly to be a bandit. He was too clean and well-groomed. In fact, he gave the impression of being a man of nobility.<br>I announced myself so as not to startle the man. He turned to me and beckoned me to approach. He introduced himself as Ryshon Hunsti and said that he was here seeking enlightenment. He asked if I was looking for the same and I replied that I was. He mentioned something vague about a sword then turned back to his vigil over the water.<br>I pressed him for more about this sword. He said it was far more than just a sword. It was a blade crafted by noble men and blessed by the gods. I asked him why he had mentioned this sword to me, and he said he could sense my holy power and knew I would use it for good.<br>Ryshon knew nothing about the current whereabouts of the sword, but he told me of another man who might. He mentioned that a dwarf named Kanthuk Ogrebane was also familiar with the sword. Ryshon gave me a note to present to Kanthuk which would ensure that he would speak with me. I yawned my thanks as fatigue began to set into all my muscles. Ryshon assured me that I could camp there as he would remain up on watch all night. I asked what he was watching for, but he had already turned back to the water and forgotten my presence. I fell into a heavy sleep.<br>When I awoke the next morning, Ryshon was nowhere to be found. I began my journey to Qeynos ... reluctantly. I wanted to sprint for Freeport and a boat that would take me to my homeland and Kanthuk. But I had made a promise to be in Qeynos by the next day, so I continued my journey, mind adrift with thoughts of this sword, &quot;forged by noble men, blessed by the gods.&quot; <br>&nbsp;<br>Gawayne Paendrag - 24th Dwarven Paladin of Brell Serillis - Bristlebane server</td></tr>
