<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101276745850761></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101276745850761><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101276745850761>a fantastic battle; serious limitations</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101276745850761#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=141146><span id= >Igon</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>4 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Feb 3rd 4:19 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Upon crossing the bridge to Southern Karana, I was greeted by a bard of fantastic power. She offered me a strange item - the skull of a cyclops. I asked her why she was presenting this to me. She merely stated that I would need it someday, then bowed and departed. I gathered up the skull, pondered its significance momentarily, then began the trip to the aviak village.<br>Along the way, I discovered what could best be described as a village of skeletons. As I am a holy paladin, I spent some time hacking apart these abominations to Norrath. I gathered up the bone chips that were left to present to my guild when I returned to Kaladim, then continued on.<br>After a long trek across the plains (including some run-ins with strange beasts I was later told were called &quot;elephants&quot;), I arrived at the aviak village. It resembled a series of bird houses, connected by a single ramp that ended at a large main house at least three giants' heights above the ground. As I inspected the structure, I saw a horrible sight. A fellow adventurer slipped from the top level and plummeted to the ground, never to rise again. I said a prayer for her soul, reminded myself to be cautious, then proceeded to the ramp.<br>There I was met by a ranger named Quisnost, who was looking for people to band together in battle against the birds. I agreed to join. The other members were Prymate, a mighty warrior, Athiena, a young but knowledgeable bard, and the magic-users Nelwen and Sanfilar.<br>Prymate and Quisnost headed to the gypsy camp in North Karana to have their souls bound close by. I led the others in several small skirmishes with the birds. The aviaks here were very similar to those of my homeland; they hit hard and can take a beating. I've always respected their fighting strength, and these early battles in Karana served to solidify that respect.<br>When the other warriors returned, we began to battle our way to the top level, or what adventurers refer to as the &quot;penthouse.&quot; We fought the lower-ranking birds, mostly darters and rooks, creatures that any of my party could have defeated on their own, although not without a struggle. A vicious harrier was our first difficult opponent. Our combined might was too much for it, but I knew facing more than one such foe at a time could be our downfall.<br>We carved our way to the penthouse and discovered six low-ranking birds waiting for us. I used some of the spells granted me by my god to Lull and Root the aviaks so that we could fight them in smaller numbers. We dispatched the first batch easily, then sat to recover and wait for more to appear.<br>The trouble began with a lowly darter. He was the first to venture into the room and the first to taste our steel and fire. However, before he fell, another aviak appeared - an avocet, the mightiest of the birds in the village. It was far stronger than any of us and the darter had distracted us enough for the avocet to sneak up and begin its assault.<br>After we killed the darter, we turned our attention to the avocet ... but before that battle even began, a harrier, stronger than the first, appeared and blitzed Quisnost. He and I bore the main brunt of the attack and we were quickly staggered. Someone sounded a retreat as the life was beaten out of us.<br>Rather than run, Quisnost and I urged our companions to fight on. We held our ground and the others quickly returned. Prymate was especially handy in this battle, slicing the foul birds with his magic blade. We focused all our energy on the avocet and soon he began to waver. The powerful bird became the first to run, but we cut him down before he could summon help.<br>Our attention quickly turned to the harrier, who was continuing his assault on Quisnost. I slashed at the feathered warrior, but soon noticed that Quisnost's wounds were critical and that my compatriots were doing far more damage than I. I stepped back from the fray and began to heal my injured comrade. While my powers are still limited, I managed to keep Quisnost standing long enough for the party to get the harrier running. We finished him off, exchanged hearty congratulations on our hard-fought victory, then sat to mend our wounds and meditate.<br>At that time, I pondered something that had bothered me much of the day. Although I initiated most of our battles with the birds, during the fights they routinely turned their backs on me to battle other members of the group, members they viewed as more powerful, more of a threat. I had to admit that despite the fact I was the most seasoned adventurer of the group, I was the weakest link in battle. I could use my battle instincts to give us an advantage, but when it came down to straight melees, I was not needed in this group.<br>We fought several more battles, then I wished my collegues luck and departed. I knew that I needed to acheive more power if I was to be a true holy paladin of Brell Serillis. I had a strange feeling that the cyclops skull I was given was part of that puzzle, part of my journey to obtaining more strength.<br>But my thoughts flickered back to my days as a young paladin and talk in the guild hall. I had often heard stories of &quot;holy swords,&quot; hidden somewhere in Norrath, waiting for a paladin of true strength and virtue to discover and wield it in righteous battle. One in particular I recalled by name.<br>I decided to continue my battles in Southern Karana for a time, but my main focus has become gathering information to begin my quest for a holy sword. I am going to seek Ghoulbane.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sun Feb&nbsp;&nbsp;3 15:26:48 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Gawayne Paendrag - 24th Dwarven Paladin of Brell Serillis - Bristlebane server</td></tr>
