<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101270121147772></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101270121147772><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101270121147772>bitter days</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=141146&mid=101270121147772#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=141146><span id= >Igon</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>4 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Feb 2nd 9:55 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I was in Firona Vie, nursing my sorrows when the letter arrived. The reason for my distress was that I lost my most loyal and valiant friend, Gwendilynne. A powerful magic user, we met as young adventurers and formed a strong friendship. We journeyed together constantly, often turning down offers to join more powerful groups so that we could stay together.<br>Our adventures led us to Crushbone, Steamfont and finally the Lake of Ill Omen. Perhaps the name should have been a warning. We spent much time in the Lake, battling the hordes of goblins and sarnaks who controlled the area. We earned numerous rewards, made numerous friends. With Gwendilynne's help, I earned much esteem in my guild for victories over the hated goblins.<br>Then the rumors reached us. Gwendilynne heard that someone found a way to reach the moon. I told her that was nonsense, but she was intrigued. She was a true adventurer and even the possibility that she could reach the moon was too much to resist.<br>I urged her to stay. She urged me to go. I told her that there was too much work for me yet in Norrath and I could not. So we parted ways; I stayed to battle the goblins and she went off in search of the moon.<br>Word reached me weeks later. Something horrible had gone wrong in her attempt to reach the moon. The magic needed to make the trip was too powerful to control. She gave her best effort, as she always had, but the strain was too much ... and my friend was lost forever.<br>I spent many weeks drowning my sorrows in drink when, as I said, the letter reached me. It was from another friend, a young warrior named Jehosophat. He and a paladin (his name escapes me, but his courage was great) requested my help. It seems they had been given the task of acquiring the heart of Ambassador D'Vinn and the head of the orc prophet, two of my old foes from Crushbone.<br>This was welcome news. Not only would I have the chance to help a friend, I could gain vengeance on some old foes and take my mind off the loss of my friend.<br>I journeyed for days across the ocean. The time passed slowly and my rage built slowly as I prepared myself for a difficult battle. I was determined to defeat D'Vinn and the prophet this time. They had handed me myriad defeats in the past, but this time I was stronger. My holy powers had grown and I knew they could not stand against me.<br>Setting foot on my home continent for the first time in months, I wept. This is where I had met my friend, Gwendilynne. I recalled the time she had saved me from certain death at the hands of undead abominations in Steamfont. I was battling alone, outnumbered, when a fireball streaked by and destroyed one of my foes. The tide turned, we emerged victorious. I smiled at my comrade, then collapsed at her feet due to my wounds. She stood watch over me until I recovered. She saved me ... and where was I when she needed me? I could have stopped her, but I let her go.<br>I rose and let out a mighty bellow. I swore I would never lose a friend again if it was in my power. I ran off towards Crushbone. I cared not if I lost my own life in the process; Jehosophat would complete his quest safely.<br>I arrived at the entrance to the cave. Jehosophat and the other paladin were already waiting. I'm sure they could sense something was wrong. I used my holy powers to prepare them for the battle and we entered the lair of the orcs.<br>Many orc guards were stationed near the entrance. They refused to attack us; they sensed our power and trembled in fear. My companions were prepared to let them be, but it had been too long since my loss and too long since my last battle. I began slaughtering every orc I laid eyes on. They tried to flee, but they could not escaped my crystallized blade.<br>Countless orcs fell before we reached the castle. We entered the throne room and discovered a group of young adventurers giving their all in combat with the orcs. I used my holy powers to heal their wounds. One, Diavola, returned the favor, using her powers to prepare us for what lay ahead. Everyone exchanged best wishes, then we were off to the tower.<br>As we climbed the steps to the tower, I took the lead, remembering how powerful our foes truly were. As I peered around the corner, I saw the dark elf Ambassador D'Vinn waiting for us. I charged him and the battle was on. My blade carved through his armor, but the evil elf used his shadow powers to sneak behind me and stab me in the back. Enraged at his cowardice, I let out a mighty yaulp and redoubled my efforts. D'Vinn began to stagger. With one final swing, he fell at my feet and expired.<br>While I healed the others, the young paladin carved the heart out of the dark elf and stowed it in a pouch. Half of the quest was complete. We just needed the prophet now.<br>Before he appeared however, we heard a savage growl. I turned to see Emperor Crush himself had arrive. He wanted our blood. He battered me mercilessly before I could gather myself and counterattack. The youngsters injured him severely while I recovered, and then it was my turn. Blood blurring my vision, I bellowed at the leader of the orcs, my sworn enemy. I lunged forth and impaled him on my blade. As I inspected the body, I discovered to my distaste that the fiend was wearing Dwarf-crafted armor. I removed it and donned the armor myself. It was time for that armor to protect the forces of good.<br>As we continued to wait for the prophet, we were startled by the unexpected ... the return of D'Vinn! Some how, he was able to defy death with his evil powers. After another fierce battle, he fell once again. I took his heart this time and prayed to Brell Serillis that his evil was removed from Norrath forever.<br>The prophet appeared shortly thereafter and fell easily. The young paladin severed the head, placed it in his backpack and we departed, quest complete.<br>The orc guards cowered before us as we showed them the head of their prophet. They feared our power, and we gave them reason to. I sent as many as I saw to join their leaders in hell before I left Crushbone.<br>My companions and I journeyed to Kaladim to show our respect for the warriors guild. We presented them with the belts and shoulder pads of our orc foes and they rewarded us with gold and weapons, though we asked for none in return. After that, we retired to an inn to relive our adventure.<br>The next morning, I parted ways with Jehosophat. He had joined a mighty guild hall and was off to join them on more quests. I could not join them, he said, but I made him promise to summon me again if he needed my help. He agreed, we exchanged best wishes, and then he was off.<br>I was lost now. I had no real purpose. One friend dead, the other no longer needed me. I had become accustommed to traveling on my own or with a select few. I felt the best way to acheive my true power was spending time in isolation, one-on-one with my foes, meditating on the teachings of Brell Serillis.<br>However, something had changed with the passing of Gwendilynne. I felt empty without her company. The adventure with Jehosophat emphasized that feeling. I needed to journey with others, to assist them in their goals ... and, just maybe, they could assist me in mine.<br>I decided to depart the shores of Faydwer. Too many strong memories of my time with Gwendilynne. I headed to the port. I planned to journey to Antonica, a land unknown to me, and see what it offered.<br>As I boarded the ship, I took one last look at my homeland. I knew not when I would return, but I knew some day I would. I would return when I had brought honor to my guild, to the Paladins of Brell Serillis.<br>And I promised myself one thing as the ship left the docks: If there truly was a way to reach the moon, I would get there. For my friend.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Feb&nbsp;&nbsp;2 21:02:09 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Gawayne Paendrag - 24th Dwarven Paladin of Brell Serillis - Bristlebane server</td></tr>
